            <!-- FAQ Section -->
            <div class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
              <div class="space-y-4">
                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button class="faq-question w-full px-6 py-4 text-left font-medium text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50 flex justify-between items-center" type="button">
                    <span>What is an x-intercept?</span>
                    <svg class="w-5 h-5 transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                      <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
                    </svg>
                  </button>
                  <div class="faq-answer hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
                    <p>The x-intercept is the point where a line crosses the x-axis. At this point, the y-coordinate is always zero. To find it, set y = 0 in your equation and solve for x. For example, if your line has the equation y = 2x + 4, setting y = 0 gives 0 = 2x + 4, which solves to x = -2. Therefore, the x-intercept is at point (-2, 0).</p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button class="faq-question w-full px-6 py-4 text-left font-medium text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50 flex justify-between items-center" type="button">
                    <span>What is a y-intercept?</span>
                    <svg class="w-5 h-5 transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                      <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
                    </svg>
                  </button>
                  <div class="faq-answer hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
                    <p>The y-intercept is the point where a line crosses the y-axis. At this point, the x-coordinate is always zero. To find it, set x = 0 in your equation and solve for y. In slope-intercept form (y = mx + b), the y-intercept is simply 'b'. For instance, in the equation y = 3x - 5, the y-intercept is -5, giving you the point (0, -5).</p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button class="faq-question w-full px-6 py-4 text-left font-medium text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50 flex justify-between items-center" type="button">
                    <span>How do you find intercepts from standard form?</span>
                    <svg class="w-5 h-5 transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                      <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
                    </svg>
                  </button>
                  <div class="faq-answer hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
                    <p>For an equation in standard form (Ax + By = C): To find the x-intercept, set y = 0 and solve for x, giving x = C/A. To find the y-intercept, set x = 0 and solve for y, giving y = C/B. For example, with 2x + 3y = 6: the x-intercept is found by setting y = 0, so 2x = 6, giving x = 3 or point (3, 0). The y-intercept is found by setting x = 0, so 3y = 6, giving y = 2 or point (0, 2).</p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button class="faq-question w-full px-6 py-4 text-left font-medium text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50 flex justify-between items-center" type="button">
                    <span>Can a line have no intercepts?</span>
                    <svg class="w-5 h-5 transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                      <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
                    </svg>
                  </button>
                  <div class="faq-answer hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
                    <p>Yes, certain lines can have missing intercepts. A horizontal line at y = k (where k ‚â† 0) has a y-intercept at (0, k) but no x-intercept because it never crosses the x-axis. A vertical line at x = h (where h ‚â† 0) has an x-intercept at (h, 0) but no y-intercept because it never crosses the y-axis. A line passing through the origin (0, 0) has both intercepts at the same point.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button class="faq-question w-full px-6 py-4 text-left font-medium text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50 flex justify-between items-center" type="button">
                    <span>What if the intercept is negative?</span>
                    <svg class="w-5 h-5 transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                      <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
                    </svg>
                  </button>
                  <div class="faq-answer hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
                    <p>Intercepts can absolutely be negative. A negative x-intercept means the line crosses the x-axis to the left of the origin. A negative y-intercept means the line crosses the y-axis below the origin. The calculation process remains the same - simply preserve the negative sign in your answer. For example, if you calculate x = -4 for the x-intercept, your intercept point is (-4, 0).</p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button class="faq-question w-full px-6 py-4 text-left font-medium text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50 flex justify-between items-center" type="button">
                    <span>How do I graph a line using intercepts?</span>
                    <svg class="w-5 h-5 transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                      <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
                    </svg>
                  </button>
                  <div class="faq-answer hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
                    <p>Graphing using intercepts is one of the fastest methods. First, calculate both the x-intercept and y-intercept. Plot these two points on your coordinate plane. Since two points define a line, simply draw a straight line through both intercept points, extending it in both directions. This method works perfectly for all linear equations except vertical and horizontal lines that pass through the origin.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button class="faq-question w-full px-6 py-4 text-left font-medium text-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-50 flex justify-between items-center" type="button">
                    <span>What's the relationship between slope and intercepts?</span>
                    <svg class="w-5 h-5 transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                      <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
                    </svg>
                  </button>
                  <div class="faq-answer hidden px-6 pb-4 text-gray-600">
                    <p>The slope and intercepts are connected through the line's equation. If you know the y-intercept (b) and the slope (m), you can find the x-intercept using x = -b/m. Conversely, if you know both intercepts, you can calculate the slope as m = -y-intercept/x-intercept. This relationship is particularly useful when converting between different forms of linear equations or when verifying your calculations.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
